Equation (1) expresses that the power produced by the MCT is proportional to the cube of the current speed in the turbine cross section.For more accuracy, the swell effect, which is considered as the most disturbing one for the considered resource model, is added based on Stokes model. This model is a very classical first-order model used to predict the swell influence in the sea water column. For a given swell amplitude H, a period T, a swell length L and ground sea depth d, the speed potential ϕ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\phi$$\end{document} can be calculated for each depth z. The water speed created by the swell effect can be deduced by a spatial derivation of this potential [20].2Vswell=gradϕϕ=-HLTcosh2πz+dLsinh2πdLsin2πtT-xL\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\left\{ \begin{array}{l} V_{swell}=\mathrm {grad} \phi \\ \phi =-\frac{HL}{T}\frac{\mathrm {cosh}2\pi \left( \frac{z+d}{L}\right) }{\mathrm {sinh2} \pi \left( \frac{d}{L}\right) }\mathrm {sin}2\pi \left( \frac{t}{T}-\frac{x}{L}\right) \end{array} \right.$$\end{document}This speed disturbance, calculated for typical intense swell specifications, can be added to the predicted tidal current speed to estimate how the swell can disturb the tidal current values in the turbine disk.

Thus, the PMCT\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
